Please see [Tour.tsx](mdc:packages/cds-web2/src/tour/Tour.tsx) and [DatePicker.tsx](mdc:packages/cds-web2/src/dates/DatePicker.tsx) for exemplary components.

## Accessibility Guidelines

- If a component has accessibility props, assign values to them. Otherwise, assign appropriate ARIA attributes for all interactive elements when you are not using semantic HTML elements. An accessibility prop usually has the string "accessibility" in it. One example is "accessibilityLabel". If you cannot confidently determine how to use accessibility props for a component that has them, fallback to using ARIA attributes
- Provide descriptive labels for all interactive elements
- Associate form inputs with helper text using aria-describedby
- Use semantic HTML elements whenever possible
- Ensure keyboard navigation works for all interactive components
- Follow WCAG 2.1 AA standards for color contrast
- Support screen readers by providing descriptive labels and instructions
- Test with assistive technologies to ensure compatibility

## Styling

### Linaria

- Always use linaria for delcaring and applying classNames
- Always import css and cx from @linaria/core:

  ```ts
  import { css, cx } from '@linaria/core';
  ```

### Creating Styles

Use css template literals for static styles, defined outside components:

```ts
const baseStyle = css`
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  padding: var(--space-4);
  border-radius: var(--borderRadius-200);
  background-color: var(--color-bgPrimary);
`;
```

### Applying Classes

- Merge classes using `cx` in the component's className prop:

```ts
import { cx } from "@coinbase/cds-web";

className={cx(
  baseStyle,                      // Base styles first
  isCompact && compactStyle,      // Conditional computed styles
  className,                      // User-provided className last
)}
```

### Other Style Best Practices

- Use css variables and theme tokens for colors, spacing, and typography instead of hardcoded values (see [theme.ts](mdc:packages/cds-common2/src/core/theme.ts))
- Use data attributes for state-based styling: `data-active`, `data-disabled`, `data-variant`, `data-filled`
- Never hardcode colors or spacing values
